to use reflection directly. The proxy is from the reflection package, but it's a public API, so maybe that's acceptable. I wonder if it could help avoid using Method.invoke, though it might add complexity to testing. Alternatively, I considered using java.beans.EventHandler, but no. I think it might be better to prototype in a test environment with JUnit and use plain Java with the necessary dependencies in Gradle. I'll need to check which jars are required.\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_YzIIjNehheHTsJ2mkAi3kvwk|fc_0bf38c1e278fd09f0169f293b7cff8819c8dce8aec65602b8a", "name": "bash", "arguments": {"command": "find ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1 -path '*objenesis*2*/*.jar' -o -path '*minlog*/*.jar' | head -20"}, "partialJson": "{\"command\":\"find ~/.gradle/caches/modules-2/files-2.1 -path '*objenesis*2*/*.jar' -o -path '*minlog*/*.jar' | head -20\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "gpt-5.5", "usage": {"input": 1285, "output": 1407, "cacheRead": 33792, "cacheWrite": 0, "totalTokens": 36484, "cost": {"input": 0, "output": 0, "cacheRead": 0, "cacheWrite": 0, "total": 0}}, "stopReason": "toolUse", "timestamp": 1777505181678, "responseId": "resp_0bf38c1e278fd09f0169f2939e9c84819cbeb1a98671eaf180"}}
